{
  "answer": "**The dream-narrative poem is \"Maa ka Khwab\" (\"Mother's Dream\"), chapter 29 of *Bang-E-Dara Part 1* by Allama Iqbal.[^1]**\n\nThis matches the description: the grieving mother dreams of a procession of boys \"in robes of emerald green arrayed, / a burning lamp each hand displayed,\" recognizes her dead son at the back \"with no lamp\" lit, reproaches him for leaving her alone, and receives his reply.[^2]\n\nThe child's verbatim closing two lines are:\n\n> \\\"Do you now see what has become of it?  \n> It is your tears that have extinguished it.\\\"[^3]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, [chapter 29](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/29-maa-ka-khwab/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/29-maa-ka-khwab/translation/#p-068672).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/29-maa-ka-khwab/translation/#p-4feffc).",
